    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-07-25T05:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-07-25T05:30:00-05:00" n="336"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d336">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">788.00/7–2553: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 336<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Iran (<persName corresp="#p_MGH1" type="from"
                            >Mattison</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d336fn1">Repeated to London and Salzburg for Ambassador
                            <persName corresp="#p_HLW1">Henderson</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tehran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-07-25T14:00:00+03:30"
                            >July 25, 1953—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>163. Following is analysis current position <persName corresp="#p_MM1"
                        >Mosadeq</persName> Government: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>
                            <persName corresp="#p_MM1">Mosadeq</persName> unsure as yet how to
                            exploit July 21 demonstrations.<note n="2" xml:id="d336fn2">Chargé
                                    <persName corresp="#p_MGH1">Mattison</persName> reported in
                                telegram 142, July 22, that the Tudeh demonstrations the previous
                                day were large and well-organized, and that the Tudeh masses
                                displayed a high degree of discipline. (788.00/7–2253) The Embassy
                                also transmitted a review of the demonstrations to the Department in
                                despatch 56, July 24. (788.00/7–2453)</note> Has not yet shown his
                            hand. There are indications, however, that he not adverse to using
                            demonstrations as means emphasizing Tudeh danger to Western
                            world.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>
                            <persName corresp="#p_MM1">Mosadeq</persName> uncertain as to future
                            course for number of reasons: <list>
                                <label>a.</label>
                                <item>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_EGDD1">Eisenhower</persName>–<persName
                                        corresp="#p_MM1">Mosadeq</persName> exchange.</item>
                                <label>b.</label>
                                <item>Continued absence Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_HLW1"
                                        >Henderson</persName> and uncertainty date return.</item>
                                <label>c.</label>
                                <item>Fact that “negotiations” with USSR have not caused evidence
                                    alarm on our part, and have not so far produced any concrete
                                    result that could be publicly exploited.</item>
                                <label>d.</label>
                                <item>Extreme Tudeh strength displayed at July 21
                                    demonstrations.</item>
                                <label>e.</label>
                                <item>Domestic economic ills.</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>There are indications that above factors (principally <persName
                                corresp="#p_EGDD1">Eisenhower</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_MM1"
                                >Mosadeq</persName> exchange) have made some of <persName
                                corresp="#p_MM1">Mosadeq</persName>’s supporters hesitate and
                            question to themselves whether they should continue support. There has
                            been no open doubt expressed but hesitation is evident particularly
                            among more moderate supporters.</item>
                        <pb facs="0765" n="739" xml:id="pg_739"/>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>In belief, situation continues uncertain. If present trends persist
                            over a period of time whereby each step <persName corresp="#p_MM1"
                                >Mosadeq</persName> takes gradually increases his dependence on
                            Tudeh, results too obvious to need elaboration.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MGH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mattison</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
